        "created_at": "2019-08-22T18:59:52Z",
        "updated_at": "2019-08-22T19:00:29Z",
        "author_association": "OWNER",
        "body": "> Also glit (as a command) seems secondary to this tech as a bash-prompt. In the readme, you should present it as secondary or an \"also\" thing.\r\n\r\nTo clarify on this point as well, `glit` does 3 things:\r\n\r\n- `glit` reads the git repository using libgit2 to get the branch, upstream, modified files, etc\r\n- `glit` parses its format language into an AST\r\n- `glit` interprets that AST with information from the git repository to produce the output\r\n\r\nThe only reason a shell script is necessary is to actually automatically run the program and put its output in the variable that the shell prompt reads when it presents the prompt.\r\n\r\nColor support is done through ANSI escape codes, and the only Bash specific part so far is the option to output special escapes to prevent line wrapping issues in BASH (`-b` flag).  *In theory,* as long as the platform supports ANSI escape codes, then it is 100% supported as long as the user writes a custom script.\r\n\r\nAgain, thank you for asking these questions and making these suggestions!"
    },
